                <t:place type="monastery" subtype="institution">
                    <t:placeName xml:id="n1" xml:lang="gez">ዳጋ፡ እስጢፋኖስ፡</t:placeName>
                    <t:placeName corresp="#n1" xml:lang="gez" type="normalized">Dāgā
                        ʾƎsṭifānos</t:placeName>
                    <t:placeName xml:id="n2" xml:lang="gez" type="alt">ደብረ፡ ዳጋ፡ እስጢፋኖስ፡</t:placeName>
                    <t:placeName corresp="#n2" xml:lang="gez" type="normalized">Dabra Dāgā
                        ʾƎsṭifānos</t:placeName>
                    <t:country ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3010Ethiop">ʾItyoṗyā</t:country>
                    <region notBefore="1991" type="RegionalState" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1426Amhara">ʾAmharā kǝllǝl</region>
                    <region notAfter="1974" type="province" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1713Bagemd">Bagemdǝr</region>
                    <t:settlement type="zone" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6544NorthGondar">Samen Gondar</t:settlement>
                    <t:location>
                        <t:geo>11.8961 37.3098</t:geo>
                    </t:location>
                    <t:note>
                        <t:date type="foundation" notBefore="1400" notAfter="1499" cert="low" precision="low">15th cent.</t:date>
                        <t:desc type="foundation">Although it is said to have been founded by
                                <t:roleName type="title">Saint</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5365hirutaA">Ḫiruta ʾAmlāk</t:persName> (<t:date notBefore="1200" notAfter="1299" precision="low">13th cent.</t:date>),
                            allegedly sent there by its spiritual father <t:roleName type="title">ʾabbā</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5631IyasusM">ʾIyasus Moʾa</t:persName>, this is now
                            believed to be a historical reconstruction linked to the attempts by the
                            networks of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0327DHE">Dabra Ḥayq
                                ʾƎsṭifānos</t:placeName> and <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2297DabraL">Dabra
                                Libānos</t:placeName> to take possession of this monastery. There is
                            in fact no information on the monastery's history before the <t:date notBefore="1400" notAfter="1499">15th cent.</t:date>
                  </t:desc>
                        
                        <t:ab type="history">During the <t:date notBefore="1400" notAfter="1499">15th
                                cent.</t:date>, the monastic life expanded at Dāgā ʾƎsṭifānos and the
                            monastery benefitted from land grants, royal burials and artistic
                            realizations. During the <t:date notBefore="1550" notAfter="1599">second
                                half of the 16th cent.</t:date>, the monastery was still used as a
                            mausoleum for the members of the royal family and seems to have been
                            very prosperous. <t:date notBefore="1563" notAfter="1574">Between 1563 and
                                1574</t:date>, <t:roleName type="title">mamhǝr</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS13661GabraKr">Gabra Krǝstos</t:persName> restored the
                            church with the support of <t:roleName type="title">kantibā</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4342GabraMi">Gabra Mikāʾel</t:persName>. The monastery
                            supported <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS8550sardaDe">Śarṣa Dǝngǝl</t:persName> in the wars
                            against the Muslims and, in turn, received lands in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2522Daq">Daq</t:placeName>. At the end of <t:date when="1646">1646</t:date>, <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</t:persName> gave the monastery
                            lands in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6567Derdera">Dǝrdǝrā</t:placeName> and, later,
                            in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6463Zebed">Zǝbǝd</t:placeName>. In <t:date when="1646">1646</t:date>, he also decided to rebuild the church, which was
                            completed <t:date notBefore="1651" notAfter="1653">between 1651 and
                                1653</t:date>. However, the church burnt down again in <t:date when="1714">1714</t:date>. Following the foundation of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC4970NargaS">Nārgā Śǝllāse</t:placeName> by <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS2682BerhanM">Bǝrhan Mogasā</t:persName>, some of the lands
                            traditionally attributed to Dāgā ʾƎsṭifānos were given to
                            the new monastery, causing conflicts. The church was burnt down again in
                            approx. <t:date when="1880" cert="low">1880</t:date> and reconstructed with
                            the present octagonal building.</t:ab>
                   
                        
                        <t:ab type="description">The monastery of Dāgā ʾƎsṭifānos is located on the
                            small island of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2419Daga">Dāgā</t:placeName>, on the
                            eastern side of the main island of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2522Daq">Daq</t:placeName> at the centre of lake <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC5888Tana">Ṭānā</t:placeName>. The history of the monastery and of its monks can
                            be broadly reconstructed thanks to its important library of manuscripts:
                                <t:num>67</t:num> were microfilmed by <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5072Hammersc">Ernst Hammerschmidt</t:persName> and catalogued by Six; approx.
                                <t:num>40</t:num> were microfilmed by the <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0332EMML">EMML</t:placeName> project and <t:num>28</t:num> are at the <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0303BNF">Bibliothèque Nationale de France</t:placeName>. </t:ab>
                    </t:note>
